Inflation in Europe has leaped over food
The fast-tracking inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
The November price rise in 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, with a registered annual inflation of 3.1 per cent after 2.6 per cent in October, announced by the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union.
The official forecast was only 3 per cent, according to Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central bank (ECB), the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the basic interest rate by reducing together with rising prices of raw materials and falling unemployment leading to inflationary spirals.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below two percent, but it is close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to "daunt" inflation so that it will not have to do anything later on.
In Germany, November inflation represents 3.3 percent of the 15 - year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has risen due to rising food and energy prices.
The term wheat prices have risen by 88 per cent, and soybean rates have reached the highest levels since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay substantially more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in world markets rose by 52 percent in this year, and last month it was already one barrel of black gold of almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will drop from 2.1 per cent in 2008 to 2.5 in 2009, however, it will already fall to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate will remain approximately 3 per cent over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double the interest rates during 2008.
