Congress approved the transfer of MiFID valid since 1 November.
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations which were concluded today by the vote of the Congress on the amendments incorporated by the Senate in the draft law, the government submitted to the public hearing of the regulation developing the new law with a view to the entry into force of the two before the end of the year.
The representatives of the individual parties have consistently raised the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the bodies necessary for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, foresees the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and supports cooperation between individual supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will allow financial advice services to be provided to both specialised companies and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial services (ESIs), financial consultancy companies (AFIs) that are associated with securities companies, brokerage offices with securities and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for operations with financial instruments is expanding by joining regulated secondary markets with multilateral trading systems and internalisation systems of orders that will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law also obliges investment service providers to disseminate on the market information on key aspects of their trade profile, exposure to risk and how to compensate for risk, and requires a statement of all operations carried out to simplify surveillance by the CNMV.
During the negotiations in the Congress Trade Committee, several adjustments were included, including those that included the recognition of securitised claims as a "complex" financial instrument in view of the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the USA with high risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legalize the functions that baccalaers in the economics and management of the enterprise 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977, which sets out the professional functions reserved for the economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an external intermediary, will not require authorisation from the CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and customer acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
