Concerns over the new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
There is a dispute between Russia and Ukraine about the price of natural gas, thus increasing the risk that Russian deliveries of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is driven by pipeline through Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kyev warned that if Moscow raises the price of gas to Ukraine, Russia will be charged higher transit charges.
The previous dispute between the two last year has reduced deliveries to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state owned a gas monopoly, Gazprom, is trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more because it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it might mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its gasprom deliveries.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," said Ukrainian Minister of Economy Anatolij Kinach to Reuters.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments concerning the amount of transit charges (to Western Europe) across Ukraine."
The latest major dispute between Moscow and Kiev has reduced the supply from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This led to a crushing decline in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas represents one quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the largest gas supply in the world, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
